subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#historyNote
object: A note about the past state/use/meaning of a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note
object: A general note, for any purpose.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#mappingRelation
object: These concept mapping relations mirror semantic relations, and the data model defined below is similar (with the exception of skos:exactMatch) to the data model defined for semantic relations. A distinct vocabulary is provided for concept mapping relations, to provide a convenient way to differentiate links within a concept scheme from links between concept schemes. However, this pattern of usage is not a formal requirement of the SKOS data model, and relies on informal definitions of best practice.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrowerTransitive
object: By convention, skos:narrowerTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower
object: Relates a concept to a concept that is more specific in meaning.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader
object: Broader concepts are typically rendered as parents in a concept hierarchy (tree).

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core
object: An RDF vocabulary for describing the basic structure and content of concept schemes such as thesauri, classification schemes, subject heading lists, taxonomies, 'folksonomies', other types of controlled vocabulary, and also concept schemes embedded in glossaries and terminologies.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrowerTransitive
object: skos:narrowerTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:narrower.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader
object: Relates a concept to a concept that is more general in meaning.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition
object: A statement or formal explanation of the meaning of a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exactMatch
object: skos:exactMatch is used to link two concepts, indicating a high degree of confidence that the concepts can be used interchangeably across a wide range of information retrieval applications. skos:exactMatch is a transitive property, and is a sub-property of skos:closeMatch.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#memberList
object:
For any resource, every item in the list given as the value of the
      skos:memberList property is also a value of the skos:member property.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core
object: Participants in W3C's Semantic Web Deployment Working Group.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#changeNote
object: A note about a modification to a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
object: skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise disjoint properties.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#semanticRelation
object: This property should not be used directly, but as a super-property for all properties denoting a relationship of meaning between concepts.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hiddenLabel
object: skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise disjoint properties.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel
object: The preferred lexical label for a resource, in a given language.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hiddenLabel
object: The range of skos:hiddenLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel
object: A resource has no more than one value of skos:prefLabel per language tag, and no more than one value of skos:prefLabel without language tag.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme
object: A concept may be a member of more than one concept scheme.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme
object: Relates a resource (for example a concept) to a concept scheme in which it is included.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#semanticRelation
object: Links a concept to a concept related by meaning.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#ConceptScheme
object: A set of concepts, optionally including statements about semantic relationships between those concepts.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
object: Acronyms, abbreviations, spelling variants, and irregular plural/singular forms may be included among the alternative labels for a concept. Mis-spelled terms are normally included as hidden labels (see skos:hiddenLabel).

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broaderTransitive
object: By convention, skos:broaderTransitive is not used to make assertions. Rather, the properties can be used to draw inferences about the transitive closure of the hierarchical relation, which is useful e.g. when implementing a simple query expansion algorithm in a search application.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#notation
object: By convention, skos:notation is used with a typed literal in the object position of the triple.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrowMatch
object: skos:narrowMatch is used to state a hierarchical mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#notation
object: A notation, also known as classification code, is a string of characters such as "T58.5" or "303.4833" used to uniquely identify a concept within the scope of a given concept scheme.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote
object: A note that helps to clarify the meaning and/or the use of a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#OrderedCollection
object: An ordered collection of concepts, where both the grouping and the ordering are meaningful.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broadMatch
object: skos:broadMatch is used to state a hierarchical mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#mappingRelation
object: Relates two concepts coming, by convention, from different schemes, and that have comparable meanings

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hasTopConcept
object: Relates, by convention, a concept scheme to a concept which is topmost in the broader/narrower concept hierarchies for that scheme, providing an entry point to these hierarchies.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Collection
object: Labelled collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed under a 'node label' in the hierarchy.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#topConceptOf
object: Relates a concept to the concept scheme that it is a top level concept of.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#editorialNote
object: A note for an editor, translator or maintainer of the vocabulary.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower
object: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hiddenLabel
object: A lexical label for a resource that should be hidden when generating visual displays of the resource, but should still be accessible to free text search operations.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#memberList
object: Relates an ordered collection to the RDF list containing its members.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel
object: The range of skos:prefLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example
object: An example of the use of a concept.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#closeMatch
object: skos:closeMatch is used to link two concepts that are sufficiently similar that they can be used interchangeably in some information retrieval applications. In order to avoid the possibility of "compound errors" when combining mappings across more than two concept schemes, skos:closeMatch is not declared to be a transitive property.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#member
object: Relates a collection to one of its members.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
object: An alternative lexical label for a resource.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept
object: An idea or notion; a unit of thought.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broaderTransitive
object: skos:broaderTransitive is a transitive superproperty of skos:broader.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
object: The range of skos:altLabel is the class of RDF plain literals.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#relatedMatch
object: skos:relatedMatch is used to state an associative mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#ConceptScheme
object: A concept scheme may be defined to include concepts from different sources.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#ConceptScheme
object: Thesauri, classification schemes, subject heading lists, taxonomies, 'folksonomies', and other types of controlled vocabulary are all examples of concept schemes. Concept schemes are also embedded in glossaries and terminologies.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower
object: Narrower concepts are typically rendered as children in a concept hierarchy (tree).

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader
object: By convention, skos:broader is only used to assert an immediate (i.e. direct) hierarchical link between two conceptual resources.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exactMatch
object: skos:exactMatch is disjoint with each of the properties skos:broadMatch and skos:relatedMatch.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel
object:
skos:prefLabel, skos:altLabel and skos:hiddenLabel are pairwise
      disjoint properties.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#related
object: Relates a concept to a concept with which there is an associative semantic relationship.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#OrderedCollection
object: Ordered collections can be used where you would like a set of concepts to be displayed in a specific order, and optionally under a 'node label'.

subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note
object: This property may be used directly, or as a super-property for more specific note types.
